# Light &amp; Dark Mode in Jetpack Compose: Building a Seamless UI | by Dinesh N | Medium

# Light & Dark Mode in Jetpack Compose: Building a Seamless UI
[](/@dinesh.prabha1205?source=post_page---byline--b194eeda7ad0---------------------------------------)[Dinesh N](/@dinesh.prabha1205?source=post_page---byline--b194eeda7ad0---------------------------------------)Follow3 min read·Apr 3, 2025[
](/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F_%2Fvote%2Fp%2Fb194eeda7ad0&operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F%40dinesh.prabha1205%2Flight-dark-mode-in-jetpack-compose-building-a-seamless-ui-b194eeda7ad0&user=Dinesh+N&userId=b0666c47c459&source=---header_actions--b194eeda7ad0---------------------clap_footer------------------)--

[](/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F_%2Fbookmark%2Fp%2Fb194eeda7ad0&operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F%40dinesh.prabha1205%2Flight-dark-mode-in-jetpack-compose-building-a-seamless-ui-b194eeda7ad0&source=---header_actions--b194eeda7ad0---------------------bookmark_footer------------------)Listen

Share

Ever opened an app in the middle of the night and felt **personally attacked** by the blinding white screen? Yeah, we’ve all been there. That’s why **Dark Mode** exists — to **save our eyes, our battery, and our dignity.**

In this guide, we’ll learn how to implement **Light & Dark Mode** in Jetpack Compose like a pro. By the end, your app will be smart enough to switch themes automatically and keep users happy.

**☽ Why Light & Dark Mode Matter?**

1️⃣ **User Comfort** — No one wants to be flashbanged at 2 AM. 2️⃣ **Battery Saving** — Dark mode can reduce battery drain on OLED screens. 3️⃣ **Aesthetic Appeal** — Some apps just look **cooler** in dark mode. 

** Setting Up Themes in Jetpack Compose**

Jetpack Compose uses **MaterialTheme** to manage colors, typography, and shapes. To implement Light & Dark Mode, we need two color palettes: **one for Light Mode and one for Dark Mode.**

**1️⃣ . Define Colors for Both Themes**

Create a `Color.kt` file inside the `ui.theme` package.

package com.example.themeimport androidx.compose.ui.graphics.Color// Light Mode Colorsval LightPrimary = Color(0xFF6200EE) // Purpleval LightBackground = Color(0xFFFFFFFF) // Whiteval LightText = Color(0xFF000000) // Black// Dark Mode Colorsval DarkPrimary = Color(0xFFBB86FC) // Lighter Purpleval DarkBackground = Color(0xFF121212) // Almost Blackval DarkText = Color(0xFFFFFFFF) // White**2️⃣. Create Light & Dark Themes in **`**Theme.kt**`

Now, let’s define separate color schemes for Light and Dark Mode.

package com.example.themeimport androidx.compose.material3.MaterialThemeimport androidx.compose.material3.darkColorSchemeimport androidx.compose.material3.lightColorSchemeimport androidx.compose.runtime.Composableimport androidx.compose.foundation.isSystemInDarkThemeprivate val LightColors = lightColorScheme( primary = LightPrimary, background = LightBackground, onBackground = LightText)private val DarkColors = darkColorScheme( primary = DarkPrimary, background = DarkBackground, onBackground = DarkText)@Composablefun MyAppTheme( useDarkTheme: Boolean = isSystemInDarkTheme(), // Auto-detect system theme content: @Composable () -> Unit) { val colors = if (useDarkTheme) DarkColors else LightColors MaterialTheme( colorScheme = colors, typography = Typography, shapes = Shapes, content = content )} The `isSystemInDarkTheme()` function **automatically detects** the system’s theme setting and applies the appropriate color scheme. Smart, right? 

**3️⃣. Apply the Theme in **`**MainActivity.kt**`

Finally, wrap your entire app inside `MyAppTheme` in `MainActivity.kt`.

setContent { MyAppTheme { MyScreen() }}Congratulations! Your app now **switches between Light & Dark Mode automatically** based on the user’s system settings.

** But What If Users Want to Manually Switch Themes?**

Great question! Let’s **add a toggle button** so users can manually switch between Light & Dark Mode.

**1️⃣ . Create a ViewModel to Store Theme Preference**

Since theme preference should persist, we’ll store it using **DataStore**.

First, add the DataStore dependency in `build.gradle`:

implementation "androidx.datastore:datastore-preferences:1.0.0"Now, create `ThemeViewModel.kt`:

package com.example.viewmodelimport android.content.Contextimport androidx.lifecycle.ViewModelimport androidx.lifecycle.viewModelScopeimport androidx.datastore.preferences.core.*import androidx.datastore.preferences.preferencesDataStoreimport kotlinx.coroutines.flow.Flowimport kotlinx.coroutines.flow.mapimport kotlinx.coroutines.launchprivate val Context.dataStore by preferencesDataStore("settings")class ThemeViewModel(private val context: Context) : ViewModel() { private val THEME_KEY = booleanPreferencesKey("dark_mode") val isDarkTheme: Flow<Boolean> = context.dataStore.data .map { preferences -> preferences[THEME_KEY] ?: false } fun toggleTheme(isDark: Boolean) { viewModelScope.launch { context.dataStore.edit { preferences -> preferences[THEME_KEY] = isDark } } }}Now we can **store and retrieve** the user’s theme preference!

**2️⃣ . Add a Theme Switch in the UI**

Now let’s add a **Switch button** to toggle themes.

@Composablefun ThemeSwitcher(viewModel: ThemeViewModel) { val isDarkTheme by viewModel.isDarkTheme.collectAsState(initial = false) Switch( checked = isDarkTheme, onCheckedChange = { viewModel.toggleTheme(it) } )}And use it in your screen like this:

ThemeSwitcher(viewModel)Boom! Now users can **toggle between Light & Dark Mode manually!**

** Wrapping Up**

✅ **Auto Theme Switching** — Uses system settings. ✅ **Manual Theme Toggle** — Gives users control. ✅ **Persistent Theme Preference** — Uses DataStore to remember the last setting.

** Next Steps**

 Add animations when switching themes for a **smoother experience.** Use **Dynamic Colors** for **Material You** styling.

** Final Thoughts**

Now your Jetpack Compose app has a **perfectly seamless Light & Dark Mode experience.** Your users (and their eyeballs) will **thank you.** 

Go ahead and implement it, and don’t forget — **Dark Mode makes everything look cooler.** 
